<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940110-1-00051 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940110-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Specifically, &sect;960.4(a)(1) of the proposed rule provides that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
authorized uses of subsidized advances or direct subsidies 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
include, but are not limited to, the following costs related to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the purchase, construction or rehabilitation of housing: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Real property purchase and improvement costs; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Construction or rehabilitation costs, including labor and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
materials, and contractor profit and overhead allowances; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Costs integral to the purchase or development of housing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
including, but not limited to, project-related: Architectural, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inspection and engineering fees; local building permit and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
planning fees; accounting costs; survey costs; appraisal fees; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
title insurance and other insurance costs; performance bond and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other bond fees; recording fees; credit report fees; property 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
taxes; residential relocation costs where such costs are part of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
relocation plan; legal fees; syndication fees; costs of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
translating resident documents to another language; loan 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
commitment, loan origination and other loan financing fees for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
administrative costs other than costs of administering the AHP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
award; developer's fees; and marketing costs; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) Prepayment fees imposed by the Bank on an applicant for a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidized advance that is prepaid in connection with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
purchase, construction or rehabilitation of housing, if the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant requires the borrower to pay such fee; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(v) Capitalization of reserve fund(s) necessary for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
successful operation of rental housing projects, including 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
replacement reserves, rent-up reserves, operating deficit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
reserves, and sinking fund reserves used for the transfer of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
project to nonprofit ownership when associated with a low income 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
housing tax credit transaction (26 U.S.C. 42); 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(vi) Cancellation fees imposed by the Bank on an applicant for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a subsidized advance commitment that is canceled and converted to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and disbursed as a direct subsidy in connection with the purchase, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
construction or rehabilitation of housing, if the applicant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires the borrower to pay such fee; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(vii) Refinancing of an existing loan in conjunction with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
purchase, construction or rehabilitation of housing, provided the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidized advance or direct subsidy and the proceeds of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
refinancing are used only to retire existing debt and to benefit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
low- or moderate-income households and, in the case of refinancing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in order to rehabilitate a project, there is a minimum of $2,500 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
per unit spent on such rehabilitation; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(viii) Tenant services, tenant counseling and homeowner 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
counseling costs that are a condition imposed by a lender to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
obtain financing from such lender and which are necessary for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
successful operation of the project. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940110-1-00052 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940110-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Cancellation fees identified in paragraph (vi) above, where 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
there is purchase, construction or rehabilitation of housing and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the borrower is required to pay the fee, are a cost of financing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such purchase, construction or rehabilitation and therefore are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
authorized uses of funds under the AHP. Because the advance would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be converted to a direct subsidy, such cancellation fees would be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
payable only if the application also meets the requirements for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
modification of applications contained in &sect;960.11 of the proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rule. (These requirements are discussed in greater detail in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
modification section below.) However, AHP subsidized advances or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
direct subsidies may not be used to pay for cancellation fees in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
situations where the cancellation of the advance is not part of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
restructuring that results in the purchase, construction or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rehabilitation of housing. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The conditions identified in paragraph (vii) above on the use 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of funds under the AHP for refinancing are intended to ensure that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the funds are not used by the borrower to take out its equity in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the project and to ensure that the funds are used for authorized 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
purposes under the AHP. The Board specifically requests comments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on whether the $2,500 minimum per unit is a reasonable minimum 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
amount to be required to be spent on rehabilitation in conjunction 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with a refinancing. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Questions have arisen as to whether funds under the AHP should 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be used to pay for pre-development costs that may or may not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result in the purchase, construction or rehabilitation of AHP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
housing. Pre-development costs are costs incurred prior to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
closing of a purchase, construction or rehabilitation loan for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
purpose of determining the feasibility of a proposed project. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Examples of pre-development costs include architectural and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
engineering fees, legal fees, the costs of surveys and appraisals, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
local building permit and planning fees, and earnest money 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
deposits. Since AHP applications are required to meet the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
threshold feasibility requirement provided in proposed &sect;960.9(d) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in order to be scored, authorizing the use of funds for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pre-development costs raises the question how applications for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such costs can or should be scored since the funds would be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
disbursed to applicants before the feasibility of a proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
project could be established. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition, there is a greater likelihood that costs incurred 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
during the pre-feasibility period, rather than during the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
post-feasibility period, will not result in the purchase, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
construction or rehabilitation of housing. Thus, if applications 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for AHP funds to finance pre-development costs are approved, AHP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
funds in perhaps significant amounts could go towards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pre-development costs that do not result in the financing or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
production of housing. If such costs are authorized, one option 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for dealing with this concern could be to cap the total amount of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
AHP funds that may be used for pre-development costs at a specific 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
dollar amount or percentage, such as the lesser of $200,000 or 5 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
percent of the Bank's total AHP contributions for the year. These 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
funds could be set aside and disbursed in a separate competitive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
process. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Board specifically requests comments on whether funds under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the AHP should be used for pre-development costs, how applications 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for such costs can or should be scored, and what limits, if any, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
should be placed on the amount of funds used for such purposes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the AHP. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
3. Use of Funds Requirements 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 960.4(b)(1)(i) of the proposed rule provides that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
total amount of a direct subsidy provided by the Bank to an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant under the AHP must be passed on by the applicant to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recipient. Consistent with &sect;960.9(c) of the Board's existing AHP 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulation, &sect;960.4(b)(1)(ii) of the proposed rule provides that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
an applicant receiving a subsidized advance shall extend credit to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the borrower at a rate of interest equal to the rate of interest 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
charged on the subsidized advance plus an interest rate spread 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approved by the Bank. See 12 CFR 960.9(c). These provisions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
implement section 10(j)(9)(E) of the Act, which provides that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Board's AHP regulation shall ensure that AHP subsidies provided by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Banks to applicants are passed on to the ultimate borrower. See 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
12 U.S.C. 1430(j)(9)(E). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(b)(2) of the proposed rule provides that if an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant receives a subsidized advance or direct subsidy from a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Bank or prepayment of a loan originally made under the AHP, any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interest or other income earned by the applicant on such funds, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not including any approved fee or interest rate spread charged to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the borrower, must be forwarded to the Bank to be used for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
additional AHP projects, except for interest or other income 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
earned by the applicant within 30 calendar days of receiving the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidized advance or direct subsidy or of receiving prepayment of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a loan originally made under the AHP. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(b)(3) of the proposed rule provides that a direct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidy received by an applicant from a Bank that is provided by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such applicant to a sponsor may be lent by the sponsor in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
connection with an AHP rental housing project involving low-income 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
housing tax credits (LIHTC), provided the subsidy is lent by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sponsor for a term of not less than 30 years, with all principal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and interest payments deferred until the end of such term. If 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such a loan is repaid before the end of the 30-year term, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
entire amount of the direct subsidy must be repaid to the Bank. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940110-1-00053 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940110-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
For various tax reasons, sponsors prefer to structure LIHTC 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
projects so that the AHP direct subsidy is lent to the project for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a specific long-term period, with principal and interest payments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
deferred until the end of such term. The lending of a direct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidy by a sponsor raises the question whether the subsidy is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
being passed on to the ultimate recipient, as required under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 10(j)(9)(E) of the Act and proposed &sect;960.4(b)(1)(i), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
since the subsidy ultimately is being repaid to the Bank. See 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
12 U.S.C. 1430(j)(9)(E). The Board believes that the lending of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
direct subsidy for the long-term period of income eligibility and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
affordability required by &sect;960.5 of the proposed rule, with all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
principal and interest payments deferred until the end of such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
term, satisfies section 10(j)(9)(E) and proposed &sect;960.4(b)(1)(i), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
because the project will have had the use of such funds for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
period the project must remain occupied by and affordable for low- 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or moderate-income households, even though the funds may be repaid 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at the end of such term. As discussed below, &sect;960.5(a)(1) of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule defines this long-term period generally as not less 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
than 30 years for rental housing projects. Accordingly, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
direct subsidy must be lent for a term of 30 years or more, with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
all principal and interest payments deferred until the end of such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
term. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(b)(4) of the proposed rule provides that if an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant receives a subsidized advance or a direct subsidy from a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Bank, and in turn provides both a loan and a grant to a borrower 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and charges an origination fee for providing the loan, then any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fee charged by the applicant for providing the grant may not be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
paid with the AHP subsidized advance or direct subsidy. The fee 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
may not be paid with the AHP subsidized advance because the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant has already covered the underwriting costs for the loan 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the grant in its origination fee for the loan. The fee may 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not be paid with the direct subsidy because otherwise the entire 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
amount of the AHP subsidy would not be passed through to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
borrower, as required by section 10(j)(9)(E) of the Act and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed &sect;960.4(b)(1)(i). See 12 U.S.C. 1430(j)(9)(E). 
