<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Act permits more than one possible interpretation of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement that owner-occupied housing must be ``long-term.'' One 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
way to interpret this requirement is that owner-occupied housing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
units assisted under the AHP must be added to and retained as part 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the stock of affordable housing for a long-term period. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Alternatively, the Act may be interpreted to require that under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the AHP, assistance must be provided to low- or moderate-income 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
households to make owner-occupied housing units affordable to such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
households for as long as they own the unit. These two possible 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
interpretations are incorporated in options A and B described 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
below. The Board specifically requests comments on these two 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
options. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Option A. Under option A, the long-term requirement would be met by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
providing that owner-occupied housing units be required to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
retained as affordable units for 30 years or, at the election of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the sponsor, the remaining useful life of the units, regardless of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
changes in occupancy. In order to enforce this retention 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement, owner-occupied units assisted with a loan or a grant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the AHP would have to be subject to a deed restriction or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
other legally enforceable mechanism restricting transfer of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unit to a low- or moderate-income household if the unit were sold 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
within 30 years of the purchase, construction, or rehabilitation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or prior to the end of the remaining useful life of the unit, as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the case may be. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A household purchasing such a unit would have to qualify as a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
low- or moderate-income household only at the time of purchase or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at the time of closing on the financing for the unit. A household 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rehabilitating a unit would have to qualify as a low- or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
moderate-income household only at the time the household received 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a commitment for funding through the AHP. 
