<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(7) A disclosure of whether or not the applicant has a direct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or indirect interest in the property or project. If the applicant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
has an interest in the property and the application is approved, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
then prior to the transfer of AHP funds to the project, an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
independent current appraisal of the fair market value of such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
property must be provided, unless the applicant demonstrates that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the property is being sold or otherwise transferred to the sponsor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at a price substantially below the fair market value; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(8) A statement of the project's costs; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(9) A certification from the applicant's, the sponsor's and the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
loan fund's or loan consortium's board of directors, or president 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or senior officer if so delegated by the board of directors, that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the applicant, the sponsor and the loan fund or loan consortium 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
will comply with all requirements of this part and all obligations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
committed to in the AHP application. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(c) of the Board's existing AHP regulation also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
generally requires an applicant to include in its AHP application 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the information identified in paragraphs (3) through (6) above, as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
well as any other information the Bank may require. See 12 CFR 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
960.4(c). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(c)(6) of the Board's existing AHP regulation also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires an applicant to disclose in its AHP application any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
direct or indirect interest of the applicant in the property or project. See 12 CFR 960.4(c)(6). Under &sect;960.7(a)(7)
of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule, if such an interest exists and the application is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approved, then prior to the transfer of AHP funds to the project, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the applicant generally is required to provide an appraisal of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
property or project. This is to ensure that the sales price of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such property or project owned by the applicant has not been 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inflated and that the applicant is not receiving the benefit of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the AHP subsidy. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(c)(7) of the Board's existing AHP regulation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires the applicant to include in its AHP application an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
explanation of how the applicant intends to monitor the use of any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
funds received under the AHP, including an explanation of how the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
structure of the project ensures that a preponderance of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidy is ultimately received by the targeted beneficiaries. See 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
12 U.S.C. 1430(j)(9)(D); 12 CFR 960.4(c)(7). As discussed in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
greater detail in the monitoring section below, as long as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
adequate monitoring is otherwise provided for, the proposed rule 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
does not require the applicant in all instances to monitor the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
AHP-assisted project for compliance with the long-term requirement 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the proposed rule. Accordingly, this provision of the existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulation is deleted in the proposed rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(c)(8) of the Board's existing AHP regulation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires the applicant to certify that the maximum subsidy 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limitation requirements of the AHP rule will not be violated. See 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
12 CFR 960.4(c)(8). However, since the maximum subsidy limitation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements are threshold requirements that all AHP applications 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
must satisfy (see discussion below of the 20 percent requirement), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this requirement is incorporated into proposed &sect;960.7(a)(9), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which provides generally that the applicant and sponsor must 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
certify that all requirements of the AHP regulation will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
satisfied. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.4(c)(8) of the Board's existing AHP regulation also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requires the applicant to explain in its AHP application how any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
AHP subsidy that exceeds the maximum subsidy requirements will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recaptured. See 12 CFR 960.4(c)(8). Since AHP applications must 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
satisfy the threshold maximum subsidy limitation requirements at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the outset in order to be scored and approved for AHP funding, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this issue does not arise and therefore has been deleted in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
As discussed above, the requirement in &sect;960.4(c)(9) of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Board's existing AHP regulation that the applicant's managing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
officer must certify that the AHP subsidy shall be only for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
authorized uses is expanded in proposed &sect;960.7(a)(9) to require a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
certification by the applicant, the sponsor and the loan fund or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
loan consortium not only that funds received under the AHP will be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
used for authorized uses, but also a certification of compliance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with all requirements of the AHP regulation and all obligations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
committed to in the AHP application. See 12 CFR 960.4(c)(9). In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
addition, the proposed rule requires the applicant, the sponsor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the loan fund or loan consortium, not just the applicant, as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the Board's existing AHP regulation, to make the certification 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the AHP application. This change is proposed because the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
applicant, the sponsor and the loan fund or loan consortium are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
all subject to specific requirements under the AHP and therefore 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
should be required to certify that they will comply with such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
2. Action on Applications 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
As discussed above, the proposed rule makes a major change in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Board's existing AHP regulation by taking the Board out of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approval process for AHP applications. Section 960.7(b)(1) of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed rule provides that each Bank shall review, score and take 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
action on an AHP application pursuant to the requirements 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contained in proposed &sect;&sect;960.8, 960.9 and 960.10, and shall notify 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the applicant of such action no later than 60 calendar days after 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the application due date for the AHP funding cycle. Section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
960.5(f)(1) of the existing regulation requires the Banks to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
forward to the Board their recommended applications no later than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
30 days after each offering deadline. See 12 CFR 960.5(f)(1). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Since the Banks would have greater responsibilities in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
approval process under the proposed rule, the 30-day period is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed to be extended to 60 calendar days. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.7(b)(2) of the proposed rule provides specifically 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that the board of directors of each Bank shall have the authority 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to approve or disapprove AHP applications received, and may 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
delegate such authority to the president or other senior officers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the Bank. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
