<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This proposed provision is consistent with the requirement of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
compliance with fair housing laws contained in &sect;960.5(a)(2)(i) of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Board's existing AHP regulation, and the requirement under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
existing practice that applications indicate how the sponsor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposes to affirmatively further such compliance. See 12 CFR 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
960.5(a)(2)(i). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
c. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The twenty percent requirement and alternatives.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.9(c) of the proposed rule incorporates the existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
maximum subsidy limitation requirement and alternatives contained 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in &sect;960.9 of the Board's interim rule, with minor changes in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
language and one substantive modification discussed below. See 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
12 CFR 960.9 (58 FR 17968 (April 7, 1993)). The 20 percent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement and the alternatives discussed below implement the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
maximum subsidy limitation requirement contained in section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
10(j)(9)(F) of the Act. See 12 U.S.C. 1430(j)(9)(F). Since the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
20 percent requirement or an alternative must be satisfied by all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
AHP applications to avoid over-subsidization of a project, it is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
set forth as a threshold requirement in the proposed rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) The twenty percent requirement. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 960.9(c)(1)(i) of the proposed rule provides generally 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that a Bank shall not offer subsidized advances or direct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subsidies to applicants in excess of that amount needed to reduce 
